entry.title: DevTools, Device Posture: Allow the device posture to be overridden by the DevTools
entry.content:
This patch extend the DevTools protocol to allow overriding the device posture.



It refactors the mojo implementation to make sure that only a single connection to the device service is made per window, allowing the device posture service to know which connection is emulated/overridden which will update the clients (JS bindings/MQs).



This patch also remove the device posture browsertests and make them web tests so the added codepath is tested.



Emulating the device posture should be available from every platforms therefore the patch enables the mojo bindings on platforms that do not have native support for device posture. This would be required anyway when the API will ship.



Bug: 1066842

entry.title: Move shader cache key prefix generation to gpu service.
entry.content:
Move shader cache key prefix generation from host to gpu service.

Prefix generation in host was racy since |gpu_info| needed for it

comes from gpu service via ipc. This was causing incorrect cache key

generation during shader store and load from the disk cache resulting in

cache misses.



This fix will ensure we get higher disk cache hit rates which should

improve web page load times during startup as well as improve

scrolling performance.

entry.title: arc/tracing: allow tracing former ghost window
entry.content:
Track the task ID in real time rather than check on-demand, and observe

the window even when the window is not for ARC. This allows the Tracing

object to pinpoint when the ghost window turns into a task window and

becomes traceable.



NOTES ON INCIDENTAL CHANGES



We do not need to check for ghost surface after parsing the app ID

string successfully, because the final window app ID is set *after*

assigning the final root surface. So remove that check.



This check may have been valid at some point in the past when the ghost

surface mechanism initialized the window in a different order.

Currently, when a window is used as an ARC ghost window, its app ID is

in the form of org.chromium.arc.session., so this is a redundant

check. In fact, the check gives false positives as it is now, since the

ghost surface property being checked is never cleared. So the first ARC

window started in order to boot the VM cannot be traced.



Remove an attempt in ~ArcAppPerformanceTracing to remove |this| as a

surface observer, as this is already handled by the destructor for

scoped_surface_ field.

entry.title: Unlock Resources During Eviction
entry.content:
Currently when eviction occurs resources can be locked by references on

the ActiveTree. This prevents them from being released, even when Viz

returns them.



This change sets up ClientResourceProvider to notify clients of locked

resources once they are evicted and not visible. It will be the

Client's responsibility to then remove the resource. Subsequent returns

by the parent will lead to the normal release process. However since

visibility updates can be delayed, the removal in response to eviction

can lead to the immediate release.



We are starting with Canvas resources, as they have been shown to not

release when becoming hidden. We will add other resources types later.



This reclamation is currently racey, as we still need to issue a flush

to Viz. features::kReclaimResourcesDelayedFlushInBackground provides

one way to attempt a delayed flush. Using memory-infra traces this

confirms the freeing of the GPU-side SharedImage associated with the

Canvas.



We plan to follow this with an update that adds thread specification

to viz::ResourceCallback usage in ClientResourceProvider. So that we

will be able to confirm when the releases on Main are complete, and

then explicitly flush.

ClientResourceProviderTest.EvictionUnlocksResources*

ClientResourceProviderTest.LockedReturnedResourcesReleasedDuringEviction*

entry.title: MediaFoundation: Separate L1T2 and L1T3 HW encoding flags.
entry.content:
Previously, IsSVCSupported() was used to determine if temporal layer

encoding (L1T2 and L1T3) was supported by HW and not blocked by vendor

specific limits. (Not to be confused by other "SVC modes" including

multiple spatial layers, which has never been supported for any codec.)



In order to do an experimental rollout of two temporal layers (L1T2) on

Intel devices, without also rolling out three temporal layers (L1T3),

IsSVCSupported() is replaced by GetNumSupportedTemporalLayers()

returning a value between 1 and 3.



The flag "MediaFoundationIntelVP9TemporalLayerSupport" is replaced by

flags "MediaFoundationVP9L1T2Support"/"MediaFoundationVP9L1T3Support"

to decide if 2 or 3 temporal layers should be allowed when the HW

claims to support it.



To reduce risk of accidentally shipping VP9 temporal layer encoding on

untested devices, we default the temporal layer limit to 1 for VP9 on

non-Intel or when flags are off.



Testing: Manually verified using MediaCapabilities powerEfficient and

Simulcast Playground with scalabilityMode specified and checking WebRTC

getStats()'s encoderImplementation.
